{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15380"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15380"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52599"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22470"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist is examining a duodenal biopsy from a patient with suspected coeliac disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histological features would be expected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crypt hypoplasia","Decreased crypt depth","Increased intraepithelial lymphocytes","Preserved villous architecture","Reduced mitotic activity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn coeliac disease, the duodenal biopsy typically shows \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased intraepithelial lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a key histological feature. This is accompanied by villous atrophy and crypt hyperplasia. The presence of increased intraepithelial lymphocytes is indicative of an immune response to gluten in the small intestine. Other features such as \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased crypt depth\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Epreserved villous architecture\u003C/strong\u003E are not characteristic of coeliac disease. Instead, crypt hyperplasia and villous atrophy are observed. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduced mitotic activity\u003C/strong\u003E is not expected; rather, there is increased mitotic activity in the crypts as the intestine attempts to regenerate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coeliac disease shows increased intraepithelial lymphocytes, villous atrophy, and crypt hyperplasia on duodenal biopsy.","Increased mitotic activity in crypts is a hallmark of coeliac disease as the intestine attempts to regenerate."],"references":["Caio G, Volta U, Sapone A, Leffler DA, De Giorgio R, Catassi C, Fasano A. Celiac disease: a comprehensive current review. BMC Med. 2019 Jul 23;17(1):142. doi: 10.1186/s12916-019-1380-z. PMID: 31331324; PMCID: PMC6647104","Brown NK, Guandalini S, Semrad C, Kupfer SS. A Clinician\u0027s Guide to Celiac Disease HLA Genetics. Am J Gastroenterol. 2019 Oct;114(10):1587-1592. doi: 10.14309/ajg.0000000000000310. PMID: 31274511","Espino L, N\u00fa\u00f1ez C. The HLA complex and coeliac disease. Int Rev Cell Mol Biol. 2021;358:47-83. doi: 10.1016/bs.ircmb.2020.09.009. Epub 2020 Nov 11. PMID: 33707057","Posner EB, Haseeb M. Celiac Disease. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722929"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52599"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15380"}},